1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Rb1 (11. Kf2 Nfd7 12. Rb1 {Is another way
to reach the same position.}) 11... Nfd7 12. Kf2 Rd8 (12... Qc7 {Can now be
strongly met with...} 13. Qd6 $16) 13. Qb3 (13. Ne2 Nxc5 $15) 13... Qc7 {Now
threatening to take on c5.} 14. Rd1 Rf8 $1 {Threatening to take on c5.} (14...
b6 15. cxb6 axb6 16. Ne2 Ba6 $44 {Is another way to play the position. The
positional pawn b6 is very common in this line. You can always try this. It
gives Black play against the isolated 'a' and 'c' pawns on the open files.})
15. Qb5 (15. Qb4 Nc6 16. Qa4 Na5 17. Qd4 Nc6 18. Qd2 Rd8 19. Qc1 b6 20. cxb6
axb6 $44 {As the White queen is misplaced on c1.}) 15... b6 $5 {This pawn
sacrifice, as always, is very interesting.} 16. cxb6 axb6 {Now the a3 pawn is
hanging and Ba6 is also one possibility.} 17. Qb2 (17. Ne2 Rxa3) 17... Nc5 18.
Bb5 Bd7 (18... Ba6 19. a4 {Is another possibility.} Bxb5 20. axb5 Nbd7 {
Similar to the game, only that instead of the c3 pawn there is a pawn on a3 in
the game. This position is very favourable for Black, as he has clear play
down the 'a' file.}) 19. c4 Bxb5 20. cxb5 Nbd7 $44 {Black has a super
coordinated position.} 21. Bd4 e5 22. Be3 {Black is better developed, his king
is safer; the White king isn't so safe, hence the next move is pretty obvious
yet very strong!} f5 $1 {After this, White cover for his king will be ripped
open.} 23. Qa2+ Kh8 24. exf5 e4 {The game went on for another few moves, but
Black is completely in the driver's seat as of now!} 25. g4 Ne5 26. Rd4 Rae8
27. Qe2 Qe7 28. fxe4 Qb7 29. Bd2 Ned3+ 30. Kg2 Rxe4 31. Rxe4 Re8 32. Kf1 Rxe4
33. Qg2 Ne5 34. Nh3 Nc4 35. Ng5 Rxg4 36. Qxg4 Qxh1+ 37. Kf2 Qxh2+ 38. Kf1 Nxd2+
39. Ke1 Nd3+ 40. Kd1 Nf2+ {A few things to remember in this game are: the
thematic queen side pawn sacrifice with b6 which opens the 'a' and 'c' files;
and the opening up of the king side position with f5 when the queen side has
been stabilised.} 0-1

