1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 {This is by far the main move in the
position.} Nfd7 12. a4 {So that later White can defend his c5 pawn with Qa3,
where it cannot be attacked by any Black piece.} Qc7 13. Qa3 b6 $1 {This is
the best move in the position. White sacrifices the pawn and we open lines
towards the White queen side. This sacrifice is very similar to the one which
Korchnoi used in his famous win against Kasparov in their Candidates
semi-final game 1 in 1983 - a game that is a must-watch to understand this
pawn sacrifice theme.} 14. a5 (14. cxb6 axb6 {Is analysed in the game
Ipatov-Fedorchuk.}) 14... bxc5 {If you are giving me the pawn, then I will
take it!} 15. Nh3 $6 {This gives Black easy equality. The critical move in
this position, and the one that has been lately played by Ding Liren and Wang
hao, is a6. We shall analyse it in the next game - Berry-Maki Uuro.} Ba6 $1 {
Blocking the pawn on a5 and speeding up the development. I think this move
just feels naturally right for Black.} 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black is slightly ahead
in development and can use the 'b' file to infiltrate White's position. At the
same time, it's unclear as to what the knight on h3 is doing.} 17. Qa4 (17. O-O
c4 {Threatening Ne5-d3 or Nc5 to d3 or b3.}) 17... c4 $1 {Now the Black
knights are eyeing the juicy d3 and b3 squares.} 18. O-O Rab8 {The rook also
has an opportunity just to land on b3.} 19. Rfd1 Ne5 {Threatening Nd3.} 20. Nf2
(20. Bf4 {Was more active - keeping Black in an irritating pin, which he can
wriggle out from with Qc5+; but still this seemed liked the best move.} Rfc8
21. Rab1 Rxb1 22. Rxb1 h6 $11 {Safeguarding against any back rank threats.})
20... Nc5 $1 {Now White must give up his bishop if he wants to prevent a
knight from landing on d3.} 21. Bxc5 Qxc5 $17 {Black is just clearly better
now. He is well on his way to victory because of the d3 and the b3 square
weaknesses.} 22. Rd4 Rb3 23. Rad1 Rxc3 24. Rd8 Nd3 25. Rxf8+ Kxf8 26. Qa2 Ra3
27. Qd2 Qxf2+ 28. Qxf2 Nxf2 29. Kxf2 Rxa5 30. Rd8+ Ke7 31. Rc8 Ra2+ 32. Kg3 Ra4
33. e5 Kd7 34. Rc5 a6 35. h4 Rb4 36. f4 h5 37. Kf3 g6 38. Ke3 Rb3+ 39. Kd4 Rg3
40. Rxc4 Rxg2 41. Ra4 Rg4 42. Ke3 Ke7 43. Rxa6 Kf8 44. Kf3 Rxh4 45. Ra8+ Kg7
46. Ra7 Rh3+ 47. Kg2 Rb3 48. Rc7 Rb5 49. Kg3 g5 {If White doesn't play 15. a6,
then with Ba6 exchange of bishops and c4, Black has a very comfortable
position.} 0-1

