1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Nfd7 (11... Nbd7 {Is never really
played because the b8 knight retains the option of developing more actively on
the queen side - on a6 or c6.}) 12. a4 Qc7 13. Qa3 b6 14. a5 bxc5 15. a6 $1 {
I think this is the most critical move. It kind of hems in the Black pieces.
If Black doesn't do something immediately, then he will just be worse off. So
his next move is pretty forced.} c4 $1 {Cutting off the f1 bishop and gaining
more space. Now the a6 pawn is threatened.} 16. Qa5 (16. Ne2 Bxa6 17. Qa5 {And
now Nb6 is not possible because of Bf4 followed by Bb8 and the a6 pawn will be
lost.} (17. Bf4 e5) 17... Rc8 (17... Nb6 $2 18. Bf4 Qe7 19. Bxb8 Raxb8 20. Qxa6
$18) 18. Qxc7 Rxc7 19. Ra5 {Once again threatening Bf4.} Bc8 $1 {Now the a6
bishop has done its job and Nc6 will be played.} 20. Nd4 (20. Bf4 Rc5 21. Rxc5
Nxc5 $15) 20... Nc6 21. Nxc6 Rxc6 22. Rxa7 Rxa7 23. Bxa7 $11 {The most logical
result of the game is a draw.}) 16... Nb6 $1 (16... Qxa5 {Taking the queen is
not such a great idea because the c4 pawn will become weak.} 17. Rxa5 Bxa6 (
17... Nb6 18. Ne2 Nc6 19. Ra2 e5 20. Ng3 $14) 18. Ne2 {Even though White is a
pawn down, his pieces are excellent. The rook on the 'a' file is very strong
and, combined with the bishop on e3, White has excellent compensation.} Rc8 19.
Kf2 Bb7 20. Nd4 Nc6 21. Nxc6 Rxc6 22. Be2 $14) 17. Nh3 e5 {Stopping Bf4 in
some instances.} 18. Nf2 Bxa6 19. Ng4 (19. Be2 Bb7 20. O-O N8d7 21. Ng4 Rfc8
22. Rfd1 h5 23. Nf2 Bc6 24. Rdb1 Nf8 $13 {with an idea Ne6 where the knight
will be well placed. Black has a pawn, White has more active pieces. It's a
real game and Black has his share of chances.}) 19... Re8 20. Qc5 Qxc5 21. Bxc5
Bb7 (21... N8d7 $1 {Was a stronger move and Black is more than fine.}) 22. Bxb6
axb6 23. Rxa8 Bxa8 24. Bxc4 {Now the material is even and Black will have to
struggle for a draw - which he does achieve in the end.} Bc6 25. Ke2 Nd7 26.
Ra1 h5 27. Ne3 b5 28. Bd5 Rc8 29. Bxc6 Rxc6 30. Nd5 Kh7 31. Ra7 Nf6 32. Rxf7
Nxd5 33. exd5 Rxc3 34. d6 Rc6 35. Rf5 Kg6 36. Rxe5 Rxd6 37. Rxb5 Ra6 38. h4
Ra2+ 39. Kf1 Kh6 40. Rb4 Kg6 41. Kg1 Kf6 42. Kh2 g6 43. Kg3 Rc2 44. Rb6+ Kg7
45. Rb5 Kf6 46. Rg5 Kg7 47. f4 Kh6 48. Kf3 Ra2 49. Re5 Ra3+ 50. Re3 Ra4 51. g3
Rb4 52. Rd3 {The idea with a5-a6 is one of the strongest in the Saemisch
Variation right now. But I think that with accurate play - like bc5 then Nb6
and taking the a6 pawn followed by e5 - Black keeps an equal position.} 1/2-1/2

