1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
dxc5 Qa5 9. e4 Nf6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qb3 Nfd7 12. a4 Qc7 13. Qa3 b6 {The typical
breakthrough. The most challenging move here is a5 - but what happens if White
takes the pawn? Fedorchuk just shows the easiest way to equalise the game.} 14.
cxb6 axb6 {Black has compensation for the missing pawn. Let us see why: 1.
White has two weak pawns - c3 and a4; 2. both are on open files; 3. White is
behind in development; 4. Black's knights have an excellent outpost on c5.} 15.
Nh3 Ba6 $1 {Speeding up the development.} 16. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Black's knights have
an excellent square on c5. White has an extra pawn, but I think he will be the
one who will have to fight for equality as two of his pawns - c3 and a4 - are
weaker than the b6 pawn.} 17. O-O Nac5 18. Qb4 Ra5 $1 {By doubling on the 'a'
file, Black will be able to pick off the 'a' pawn, leaving the position dead
equal.} 19. Ra3 Rfa8 20. Rfa1 Qc6 {There is just no way to save the a4 pawn.}
21. Nf4 Rxa4 22. Rxa4 Rxa4 23. Rxa4 Qxa4 24. Qxa4 Nxa4 25. Bd2 b5 $11 {The
game is dead equal. This shows that taking 14.ab6 gives Black no problems at
all.} 26. Kf2 Kf8 27. Ne2 e5 28. Ng3 g6 29. Nf1 Ke7 30. Ne3 Ndb6 31. Ke2 {This
is the first game in the database that required no variations. Black's play
was so simple: he just sacrificed the 'b' pawn to get good play down the 'a'
and 'c' files, and then used his superior pieces to win back the pawn and
equalise the position.} 1/2-1/2

