1. c4 (1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. cxd5
exd5 $5 {Usually we take back Nd5, but sometimes you might want to try and
play for a win at all costs or you might just want to surprise your opponent.
If so, then this move is an interesting idea.} 8. e3 {And we obtain the
position that is reached in the game after the 8th move.}) 1... e6 2. Nc3 d5 3.
d4 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nf6 7. cxd5 exd5 8. f3 {From quite a
different move order, we have reached the main position of this opening.} c4 $1
{This is the reason why I recommend you to play this line. If White could have
comfortably developed his bishop on d3 and then Ne2, then he would have a very
good position - similar to the famous game Botvinnik-Capablance AVRO 1938. But
here we just put a stop to Bd3 and hence we prevent White from developing
naturally.} 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. g4 $1 {Kasparov realises that king side expansion
is the only way out of this clamp that Black has put on the position.} h6 11.
Bg2 Na5 $5 {The knight naturally goes to the hole on the side of the board,
aiming for d3 later; Black can also bring his bishop into play with Bd7-a4.
With all his pieces going to the queen side, black must be careful that he
will not get mated on the king side.} 12. O-O Nb3 13. Ra2 $1 {The rook will
later be useful on the second rank for a king side attack.} O-O {Black has
finished putting his king into safety and White still cannot play e4. Black's
opening play has been very interesting.} 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. Qe1 (15. h3 {Can be
another idea to protect the g4 pawn, so that e4 is possible. But now the
problem is that the g3 knight is weak and we can play...} Qc7 16. f4 Rfe8 {
Black's position is clearly preferable: there are huge holes down the 'e' file.
}) 15... Re8 $1 {Creating latent pressure down the 'e' file and making e4
difficult.} 16. e4 $3 {What an amazing move by Kasparov! He understands
dynamics so well. The two exclamations are not for the strength of the move
but for the realisation that this is the only way to gain counterplay. He is
ready to give up a pawn in order to make e4 possible. The position is
extremely complicated, but I think Judit has her chances. The thing is that
Kasparov is a better player in such positions and hence he went on to beat
Polgar.} dxe4 17. fxe4 Nxg4 18. Bf4 (18. h3 Qh4 19. Bf4 {Transposes to the
game.}) 18... Qh4 19. h3 Nf6 20. e5 Rad8 $6 (20... Bxh3 {I was wondering why
Judit didn't take this pawn?} 21. Qd1 $5 {So that the knight can move to e4
without the queen exchange.} (21. Ne4 Qxe1 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23. Rxe1 Bxg2 24.
Rxg2+ Kh7 $15 {With two pawns less, the maximum White can try is to equalise
this position.}) 21... Bg4 22. Qc2 Nh5 23. Nxh5 Qxh5 $13 {And Black is not
standing too badly in this position.}) 21. Qf2 $1 Nh5 22. Bxh6 $1 {Kasparov is
super sharp and doesn't let such chances go by.} Re7 $2 (22... Be6 {Was
necessary...} 23. Nf5 Qxf2+ 24. Raxf2 gxh6 25. Nxh6+ Kg7 26. Nxf7 $16) 23. Nf5
$1 Qxf2+ 24. Rfxf2 (24. Raxf2 {Was also possible.}) 24... Re6 (24... Bxf5 25.
Rxf5 gxh6 26. Rxh5 {White is clearly better here. His bishop is way superior
to the b3 knight.}) 25. Be3 Bc6 26. Bf1 $1 f6 27. Bxc4 {The rest is simple.
Kasparov was able to beat the best woman player in the world.} Bd5 28. Be2 fxe5
29. Bxh5 exd4 30. Bg5 Rd7 31. Rae2 Be4 32. Nxd4 {Though Kasparov scored a
crushing win in this game, you will agree that the position arrived at from
the opening was very tense and interesting. After c4, Black really puts a
clamp on White's position. White needed to show some creativity, as was
illustrated by Kasparov. If White hadn't shown it, then he would have been
crushed!} 1-0

